  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and it is addressed primarily under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** of 1986. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, depending on the specific circumstances of the crime. Below is an overview of the penalties under federal law:\n\n### **Criminal Penalties**\n1. **Imprisonment**:\n   - Money laundering is punishable by up to **20 years in federal prison** for each count. If the offense is tied to a specific unlawful activity (e.g., drug trafficking or terrorism), the maximum sentence can increase to **life imprisonment**.\n   \n2. **Fines**:\n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering may face fines of up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - Corporations or other entities may face fines of up to **$1 million or twice the value of the property involved**.\n\n3. **Forfeiture**:\n   - The government can seize and forfeit any property involved in or derived from the money laundering activity. This includes funds, assets, and real estate.\n\n### **Civil Penalties**\nIndividuals and entities can also face civil penalties for violating money laundering laws, even if no criminal charges are filed:\n   - Civil fines can range from **$10,000 to $100,000 per violation**, depending on the severity and circumstances.\n   - Financial institutions that fail to comply with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations can face significant fines and sanctions.\n\n### **Aggravating Factors**\nPenalties can be enhanced if certain aggravating factors are present, such as:\n   - Involvement in **international money laundering**.\n   - Ties to **organized crime** or **terrorism**.\n   - Repeated or large-scale violations.\n\n### **Related Offenses**\nMoney laundering often involves other federal crimes, such as **bank fraud**, **tax evasion**, **wire fraud**, or **racketeering** (RICO violations). Convictions for these related offenses can result in additional penalties, including more prison time and fines.\n\n### **Enforcement**\nFederal agencies like the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**, the **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)**, the **Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)**, and the **Department of Justice (DOJ)** actively investigate and prosecute money laundering cases.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing allegations of money laundering, it is critical to seek legal counsel from an experienced attorney specializing in federal criminal defense.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
